	<article>

		<header>
			
			<h1>Agriculture policy discussions highlight importance of smallholder farming sector</h1>

			
			<h4>
												05 July 2011
										</h4>

					</header>


		
		
					<p>Agricultural policy analysts in the Eastern and Southern African region have called for ‘harmonisation of policies that align production to markets’. Better linking of farmers to markets was seen to be particularly important for smallholder farmers. According to press reports less than 0.5% of imported foodstuffs is sourced from within the region. Analysts argue that if more attention were paid to improving the functioning of markets, including better linking of smallholder farmers to valuable markets, then the need for subsidies would be reduced.</p><p>Already governments in the COMESA region have reached agreement on ‘the production and cross-border distribution of seeds’ of 12 crops – maize, rice, groundnut, cotton, beans, cassava, wheat, potato, sunflower, sorghum, soybeans and millet. The establishment of the common standards will facilitate the development of a regional seed trade. However, since the draft rules on cross-border distribution of seeds will need to be harmonised with ‘other aspects such as seed certification and the management of phytosanitary standards’, no immediate boost to trade is likely.</p><p>Meanwhile, a meeting of smallholder farmer organisations organised jointly by the Alliance for Commodity Trade in Eastern and Southern Africa (ACTESA), the Southern African Confederation of Agricultural Unions (SACAU) and the East African Farmers’ Federation (EAFF) has called for:</p>
<ul>

<li>more support for building the capacity of smallholder farmers to negotiate on prices;</li>

<li>more investment in the supply of agricultural inputs;</li>

<li>a greater role for farmers in seed multiplication;</li>

<li>more investment in rural collective storage facilities to reduce post-harvest losses;</li>

<li>the establishment of a farmer-owned rural finance corporation;</li>

<li>greater support to the establishment of warehouse receipt systems and agricultural commodity exchanges;</li>

<li>more investment in rural value-added processing;</li>

<li>greater use of one-stop border facilities;</li>

<li>measures to improve smallholder farmers’ access to investment financing.</li>

</ul>

		
		
				<div class="box related">
			<h3>Sources</h3>
			
