<a href="http://www.businessdailyafrica.com/Corporate+News/Comesa+states+strike+deal+to+free+seed+trade+across+borders/-/539550/1132512/-/9o520l/-/index.html" target="_self">http://www.businessdailyafrica.com/Corporate+News/Comesa+states+strike+d...</a><br/>
<i>Times of Zambia</i>, ‘Challenges of small-holder farmers’, 19 April 2011<br/>
<a href="http://allafrica.com/stories/201104190638.html" target="_self">http://allafrica.com/stories/201104190638.html</a></p>		</div>
		
		
				<div class="box">
			<h3>Editorial comment</h3>
			<p>As highlighted by the recent agreement by COMESA-region countries to liberalise the regional seed trade, opening up regional agricultural trade will require a lot of detailed negotiation, in view of the SPS and food-safety issues involved. The engagement with representative stakeholder bodies will need to be taken beyond the level of policy discussions to that of detailed practical discussions on the operational modalities, if regional agreements are not to be more breached than observed.</p><p>The discussions are likely to yield ‘low-hanging fruit’ which could be relatively easily harvested, such as the proposal for greater use of one-stop border facilities and increased support to strengthen farmers’ organisations. Other issues, such as improving the functioning of agricultural supply chains and getting to grips with investment finance issues under communal land ownership systems, are likely to prove far more difficult to address. However coherent domestic agricultural and industrial policies need to be in place at the national level before they can be harmonised at the regional level. In their absence, there are likely to remain many obstacles to expanding regional agricultural trade.</p>
		</div>
		
